Transmission electron microscope (TEM) images of CDs before and after US irradiation are shown in Fig. S11. It can be clearly observed that the aggregated CDs are forced to be dispersed after US treatment. Meanwhile, we also conducted the Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FTIR) characterizations. As shown in Fig. 3
                     a, the stretching vibrations of C–O and –COOH groups corresponding to 1238 and 1714 cm−1 for US-treated CDs are significantly weakened compared with the initial CDs, demonstrating that these oxygen-containing groups are consumed during US irradiation [24,34]. Simultaneously, we also observed an interesting phenomenon that the pH of aqueous reaction solution gradually declines with US irradiation time (Fig. 3b). What's more, increasing the amount of CDs added in reaction solution can make pH drop faster under the same conditions (Fig. S12
                     ). This phenomenon could result from the cleavage of the valence bonds of C–O and O–H on the surface of CDs. PL spectra and PL excitation (PLE) spectra of CDs suspensions irradiated for different time under US were recorded in Fig. 3c. The strongest PL peak of CDs is unchanged with US irradiation time, but the corresponding PLE peaks become red-shift due to the gradual reduction of recombination centers induced by surface groups [39]. The repeated experiments show that the sonocatalytic activity of CDs continues to decline with repeated times as well (Fig. 3d). In contrast, TiO2 exhibits superior stability in sonocatalytic activity under the same conditions (Fig. S13). All of above results can testify that the surface oxygen-containing groups on CDs are broken apart under US irradiation.
